These new empirical results, when combined with two remarkable
published examples of the separation of DM and LM in galaxy cluster
collisions, along with a host of previous but less compelling
empirical results, tell us in the clearest manner that large amounts
of galactic dark matter exist, and probably the DM is not comprised of
any common form of baryonic matter.

If one's theory proposes that the dark matter does not exist, or
exists only in small amounts, or is probably baryonic, then that
theory appears to be in trouble.

The key question, obviously, concerns the physical nature of all this
dark matter, which completely dominates the observable universe.
Happily, AGILE is now successfully in orbit and is completing its
initial testing phase.  If the dark matter is in ultracompact objects,
such as primordial black holes of planetary and stellar masses, these
objects should emit faint gamma radiation due to accretion of
interstellar matter.  AGILE might be able to detect a MWG gamma ray
halo and distinguish it from the gamma ray background radiation.  The
GLAST mission will have an even better chance of  doing so.

Alternatively, the gamma ray missions might discover radiation that is
more consistent with annihilation of WIMPS, or some form of exotic
particle.  And the LHC might help in verifying such particles.

The exciting thing is that the dark matter enigma cannot resist for
much longer the determined efforts of experimentalists to solve it.
And when we answer the dark matter riddle, we are almost guaranteed to
have a profoundly clarified understanding of the cosmos.

Robert L. Oldershaw
